dv <- with(dv, dv[!(brands == "" | is.na(brands)), ])
dv2 <- dv %>%
  mutate(Category = floor(naics_code/100))

dailyvisitsClothing <- dv2 %>%
  filter(Category == 4481)

Background on Audience and Purpose

I was hired by an investor who wants to open a Clothing store in King County. He wants to know what could be a popular and lucrative store in the area. I will do an analysis of the field to find the most popular brand(by visits) and go into further detail of the visits of the particular brand.

First, I will take a look at each type of clothing store and see which store type has the most visits on average.

dailyvisitsClothing <- dailyvisitsClothing %>%
  mutate(naics_code = case_when(
    naics_code == 448110 ~ 'Menswear', 
    naics_code == 448120 ~ 'Women`s Clothing',
    naics_code == 448130 ~ 'Children`s Clothing',
    naics_code == 448140 ~ 'Family Clothing',
    naics_code == 448150 ~ 'Accessories',
    naics_code == 448190 ~ 'Other Clothing'
  ))

On average, Children’s Clothing stores have the most daily visits.

library(gghighlight)
dailyvisitsClothing %>%
  mutate(naics_code = factor(naics_code)) %>%
  group_by(naics_code) %>%
  summarize(Avg_Visits_bd = mean(visits_by_day)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = naics_code, y=Avg_Visits_bd)) + geom_col(fill='red')+
  labs(x = 'Store Type', y = 'Average Visits per Day', title = 'Average Daily Visits by Clothing Store Type') +
  gghighlight(naics_code %in% c('Children`s Clothing'),
              unhighlighted_params = aes(size=.1), 
              label_params=list(direction='y',nudge_x=10)) +
  theme_classic(base_family='serif')

# Origin of Children’s Clothing Store Visitors Next, I will take a look at the origin of the people who visit clothing stores to find a good location for the store. A good location would probably be close/in the neighborhood where most visitors live.

Most visitors are from the Center/East of King County. A good location to open a Children’s Clothing store would therefore be in Center/East of King County.

library(tigris)
## To enable caching of data, set `options(tigris_use_cache = TRUE)`
## in your R script or .Rprofile.
mapdata <- block_groups('WA','033', cb = TRUE, progress_bar = FALSE)
## Retrieving data for the year 2021
ov2 <- ov %>%
  filter(naics_code %in% c(448130)) %>%
  group_by(GEOID) %>%
  summarise(visits = sum(visits))

map_and_data <- geo_join(mapdata, ov, by = 'GEOID', how = 'left')

Next, I will take a look at the Children’s Clothing brands that are most popular in King County.

Story: The most popular brands (brands with most visits) are The Children’s Place, Hanna Andersson, and Carter’s. However, The Children’s Place had by far the most total visits.

#top 3 brands
ChildrensClothing <- dailyvisitsClothing %>%
  filter(dailyvisitsClothing$naics_code == 'Children`s Clothing')

top3brands = ChildrensClothing %>%
  group_by(brands) %>%
  summarise(totalVisits = sum(visits_by_day))%>%
  arrange(totalVisits) %>%
  slice(4:6)

TheChildrensPlace <- dv %>%

TheChildrensPlace$wDay <- factor((weekdays(TheChildrensPlace$date) %in% weekdays1),

Since the Children’s Place had by far the most visitors, I will analyse the dispersion of the visits by day of the brand “The Children’s Place” next.

The box plot shows the dispersion of the visits by day of the brand “The Children’s Place”. It shows the min and max,the first and third quartile, as well as the mean. It is important to know the dispersion and how many people visit the store so you can plan for staff, inventory, and also what the layout of the store should look like(size, etc.). Story: The maximum of store visitors was 50 and the minimum was 14, while the average number of daily visitors was 29. 50% of the values (daily visits) were between 23 and 38.

TheChildrensPlace %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = brands, y = visits_by_day)) + geom_boxplot(col= 'darkblue') +
  labs(x = '', y = "Visits by Day", title = 'Dispersion of Visits by Day of Brand "The Children`s Place"') + theme_minimal()
